data.content:
## What happened

In C# 14, new **span overload resolution rules** cause `array.Contains(num)` to bind to `MemoryExtensions.Contains(Span<T>, T)` instead of `Enumerable.Contains(IEnumerable<T>, T)`. Expression trees don't support `Span`-based methods, so the compiled/interpreted expression throws at runtime.

## How to fix

Cast the array to `IEnumerable<T>` or use `.AsEnumerable()` to force the `Enumerable.Contains` overload:

```csharp
// Option 1: .AsEnumerable()
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => array.AsEnumerable().Contains(num);

// Option 2: Explicit static call
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => Enumerable.Contains(array, num);
```

Both approaches force the compiler to pick the `IEnumerable<T>` overload, which expression trees fully support. The same pattern applies to `.Reverse()` on arrays — use `Enumerable.Reverse(arr)` instead of `arr.Reverse()`.
